=> In Window you can use the "Windows Subsystem for Linux" (WSL) to run a Linux environment directly on Windows. This allows you to use Linux command-line tools and applications without needing a virtual machine or dual-boot setup.
To set up WSL on Windows, follow these steps:
1. Open PowerShell as an administrator and run the following command to enable WSL:
   ```powershell
   wsl --install
   ```
2. Restart your computer when prompted.
3. After restarting, open the Microsoft Store and search for a Linux distribution (e.g., Ubuntu, Debian, etc.) and install it.
  -> To install a specific Linux distribution like ubantu, you can use the following command in PowerShell:
   ```powershell
   wsl --install -d Ubuntu
   ```
4. Once the installation is complete, launch the Linux distribution from the Start menu and follow the on-screen instructions to set up your Linux user account.
5. After the setup is complete, you can start using the Linux terminal to run commands and access the Linux file system.
You can also access your Windows files from the Linux terminal by navigating to the `/mnt` directory, where your Windows drives are mounted (e.g., `/mnt/c` for the C: drive).

=> Basic Linux commands:
   -> Change directory: `cd` (For example, you want to work on F drive then you can use `cd /mnt/f`)
    -> List files and directories: `ls`
    -> Create a new directory: `mkdir <directory_name>`
    -> Remove a file: `rm <file_name>`
    -> Remove a directory: `rmdir <directory_name>`(for empty directories) or `rm -r <directory_name>` (for non-empty directories) 
    -> Copy a file: `cp <source_file> <destination>`
    -> Move or rename a file: `mv <source_file> <destination>`
    -> Display the contents of a file: `cat <file_name>`
    -> Display the current working directory: `pwd`
    
    -> To work with different different software packages, you can use the package manager specific to your Linux distribution. 
        -> For example, on Ubuntu:
            -> Install a package: `sudo apt install <package_name>`
            -> Update package lists: `sudo apt update`
            -> Upgrade installed packages: `sudo apt upgrade`
            -> Remove a package: `sudo apt remove <package_name>`
            -> Search for a package: `apt search <package_name>`
            -> List installed packages: `apt list --installed`
            -> Check for package information: `apt show <package_name>`
            -> Clean up unused packages: `sudo apt autoremove`
            -> Clean up package cache: `sudo apt clean`
            -> Check for package dependencies: `apt depends <package_name>`
            -> Check for reverse dependencies: `apt rdepends <package_name>`
            -> Check for package files: `dpkg -L <package_name>`
            -> Check for package status: `dpkg -s <package_name>`
            -> Check for package version: `dpkg -l <package_name>`
            -> Check for package architecture: `dpkg --print-architecture`
            -> Check for package source: `dpkg --print-foreign-architectures`
            -> Check for package configuration files: `dpkg --get-selections | grep <package_name>`
            -> Check for package logs: `cat /var/log/dpkg.log | grep <package_name>`

        -> Keyword used in commands:
            -> `sudo`: Run a command with administrator privileges.
            -> `apt`: It means "Advanced Package Tool". Ubuntu uses the APT package manager to:
                -> Install software
                -> Update Software
                -> Remove software
                -> Manage dependencies
                
                -> Ubuntu downloads software from repositories(Official software storage servers maintained by Ubuntu).
                    -> If latest version of software is NOT available in APT repositories. we can:
                        -> Add external repositories (PPA)
                        -> Download manually from official website
                        -> Use tools like SDKMAN, Snap, Docker etc.
                        -> Install using `.deb`, `.tar.gz`, or zip packages
                    -> Example
                        -> sudo apt install maven
                        -> sudo apt install openjdk-21-jdk
                        
            -> `<package_name>`: The name of the package you want to manage.
            -> `<source_file>`: The file you want to copy or move.
            -> `<destination>`: The location where you want to copy or move the file.
            -> `<directory_name>`: The name of the directory you want to create or remove.
            -> `<file_name>`: The name of the file you want to display or remove.

    -> Check disk usage: `df -h`
    -> Check memory usage: `free -h`
    -> Check running processes: `ps aux`
    -> Kill a process: `kill <process_id>`